<p class="m-5">
    <h5>Attribute splatting</h5>
    A technique that will help you simplfy the amount of parameters you can pass from a parant component to a child component. 
    <br />
    <a target="_blank" href="https://www.pragimtech.com/blog/blazor/blazor-attribute-splatting/">link</a>
</p>


<p class="m-5">
    <h5>Arbitrary attribute</h5>
    A technique that will help you specify which default value to prioritise when passing value from a parant component to a child component. 
    <br />
    <a target="_blank" href="https://www.pragimtech.com/blog/blazor/blazor-arbitrary-attributes/">link</a>
</p>


<p class="m-5">
    <h5>Cascading values and parameters</h5>
    A technique that will help you pass data down to any of the descendant components in the component tree and access the cascading value. 
    <br />
    <a target="_blank" href="https://www.pragimtech.com/blog/blazor/blazor-cascading-values-parameters/">link</a>
</p>


<p class="m-5">
    <h5>Multiple cascading values and parameters</h5>
    There are 2 ways to cascade values from the parent component to a child component. Cascading by type and cascading by name. 
    <br />
    <a target="_blank" href=https://www.pragimtech.com/blog/blazor/blazor-multiple-cascading-parameters/">link</a>
</p>


<p class="m-5">
    <h5>Cascading values Performance</h5>
    When the cascaded value changes all the components in the entire component tree, that use the cascaded value are automatically updated. 
    However, this constant monitoring requires resources and it is better to turn of this active monitoring when it is not required to avoid performance issues. 
    <br />
    <a target="_blank" href=https://www.pragimtech.com/blog/blazor/blazor-cascading-values-performance/">link</a>
</p>

<h5>Example of cascading value</h5>
<button class="btn btn-primary" @onclick="IncrementCounter">
    Increment Counter
</button>

<CascadingValue Value="@Counter" Name="Counter" IsFixed="false">
    <CascadingChildComponent></CascadingChildComponent>
</CascadingValue>


